ANOMALY DETECTION REDESIGN — SPEC & IMPLEMENTATION
GeoMap · March 2026

WHAT CHANGES AND WHY
The current get_anomalies_multicluster() runs DBSCAN live at render time, violating the precompute contract. It is replaced entirely by a dwell-lookup approach that is simpler, faster, and more interpretable. The core insight from the POC: the dwell table is already the compressed representation of where a target belongs. Anomaly detection is a lookup against that table, not a clustering problem.
The DBSCAN-based approach is removed. No distance-from-center arithmetic, no per-cluster statistics, no n_std slider, no fallback single-center logic.

ANOMALY SCORING MODEL
A sighting is scored as follows:
Step 1 — H3 cell lookup. Convert the sighting's lat/lon to an H3 cell at resolution 12. Expand to a k-ring of radius H3_ANOMALY_RINGS (default 1, ~20m tolerance). Check whether any cell in that ring matches any cell in the target's established dwell set.
Step 2 — Hard anomaly. If no match is found, the point is in a location the target has never meaningfully visited. Score = 1.0. Type = hard.
Step 3 — Soft anomaly. If a match is found, retrieve the visit count of the matched dwell location. Score = 1 / visit_count. A location visited twice scores 0.50. A location visited 20 times scores 0.05. The soft anomaly threshold is applied at query time in the UI — not during precompute.
Step 4 — Normal. If score is below the UI threshold, the point is normal. Not stored in the anomaly output — the full scored table is stored and the UI filters it.
This means precompute stores every sighting with its score. The UI slider is a filter on a column. No recomputation ever happens at render time.

PIPELINE PARAMETERS (fixed at precompute time)
H3_ANOMALY_RES     = 12      Same resolution as clustering. ~10m cells.
H3_ANOMALY_RINGS   = 1       k=1 neighbor ring. ~20m GPS tolerance.
DWELL_MIN_VISITS   = 3       Minimum visits to establish a location.
                              Below this, visits don't count as known territory.
These live in clustering.py alongside the existing H3 constants. Changing them requires a recompute — same contract as all other pipeline parameters.

UI PARAMETER (live, O(1) filter)
soft_threshold     slider 0.05–1.0, default 0.50
                   Points with score >= threshold shown as soft anomaly.
                   Points with score == 1.0 always shown (hard anomaly).
Operationally: threshold 0.50 means "flag any location visited fewer than 2 times." Threshold 0.10 means "flag any location visited fewer than 10 times." This is intuitive to an analyst — it maps directly to visit count.

OUTPUT SCHEMA — anomalies.parquet
target                  int
last_seen               datetime
lat                     float
lon                     float
score                   float       1/visit_count, or 1.0 for hard
anomaly_type            str         'hard' | 'soft_candidate'
nearest_dwell_lat       float       NaN for hard anomalies
nearest_dwell_lon       float       NaN for hard anomalies
nearest_dwell_visits    int         0 for hard anomalies
h3_cell                 str         cell of this sighting
Note: all sightings with score > 0 (i.e. not in a well-established location) are stored. Normal sightings — those that land in a well-visited dwell zone — are not stored. The table is small by design.

